Unary-ASM — exact specification

Unary-ASM is a low-level assembly text language where every numeric field is encoded as a run of 1 characters. Fields on a line are separated by a single 0 character. Instructions are one line each (terminated by newline). The only characters allowed in a source file are: 1, 0, and newline (\n). (Whitespace other than newline is not allowed.)

Rationale / overview

Each contiguous run of 1 encodes an unsigned integer equal to the run length (i.e., run of three 1s = value 3).

0 separates fields. Newline separates instructions.

First field on a line = opcode (a run of 1s whose length is the opcode id).

Remaining fields = operands encoded as runs of 1 (their lengths are the operand values).

Assembler maps opcodes and operands to binary bytes: each numeric value is encoded as a single byte equal to value mod 256 (so run lengths > 255 wrap; assembler will error or allow wrapping depending on a flag — by default assembler errors on run length > 255 to keep exactness unless explicitly allowed).

Binary instruction layout: fixed-length per-opcode as defined in opcode table (opcode byte followed by exactly N operand bytes). This makes encoding/decoding deterministic and simple.

Important: All concrete encoding decisions below are exact and deterministic so an assembler can be unambiguously implemented.

