1 (U+0031)

0 (U+0030) — field delimiter

newline (LF, \n) — instruction delimiter

No other characters allowed. Lines with invalid characters are assembler errors.

Field parsing rules (exact)

Given a line (sequence of 1 and 0 ending with newline):

Split the line at 0 occurrences. Each segment between 0s must be a non-empty sequence of 1 characters. Trailing or leading 0 is an error.

Let k_i be the length of the i-th 1 run (a positive integer). The first k_1 is the opcode id. Subsequent k_2, k_3, ... are the operand values.

If any k_i > 255 the assembler reports RUN_LENGTH_TOO_LONG unless invoked with --allow-wrap, in which case the assembler takes k_i mod 256 as the encoded byte (but still warns).

Example: the line 111011 (characters: 111 0 11 newline) parses to two fields: opcode 3, operand 2.

Binary encoding (exact)

Each instruction becomes a sequence of bytes.

First byte is the opcode id (value = k_1 mod 256 — default assembler errors if k_1>255).

Next bytes are operand bytes: exactly the number required by that opcode (see opcode table). Each operand byte = k_j mod 256 (same wrap rule).

There is no additional metadata in the binary; instructions are concatenated sequentially.

This makes binary decoding trivial: read opcode byte, consult opcode table for operand count, read that many bytes.

