Notes (exact):

Any finite instruction uses only a finite prefix of exponents; all but finitely many e_i are zero.

Because prime factorization is unique, decoding is unique: this is a one-to-one encoding from finite tuples of non-negative integers to positive integers.

k = 1 corresponds to all exponents e_i = 0. That is the minimal instruction (the “unit” — you requested 1 is the minimum).

If a macro needs more than the first m fields, the assembler will read as many prime-exponent positions as required by the instruction format.

