Because your phrase “reveal the whole tree of 1s composing that single 0” is slightly ambiguous, I made a precise (and useful) interpretation and documented it:

What this code does (clear spec)

Treats memory as a linear bitstring (least-significant bit = bit 0 of first byte).

Scans a byte buffer for the first bit that equals 0. (If the whole buffer is 1s, it returns a not-found result.)

When it finds the zero bit at bit-index i, it computes the maximal contiguous run of 1 bits that touch that zero bit — i.e., the contiguous group of 1 bits immediately adjacent to that zero bit, both left and right, limited to the buffer. Concretely:

Let the zero be at index i. Consider bit positions ... i-2, i-1, i, i+1, i+2 ...

Expand left while bits are 1, expand right while bits are 1.

Return:

the zero-bit index i (64-bit in RAX) and

a mask of up to 64 bits (in RDX) containing the contiguous 1 run mapped so its LSB corresponds to the lowest bit of that run (so the run can be 0..64 bits long). If the run is longer than 64 bits, the mask reflects only the portion within the 64-bit window and the length returned (in RCX) indicates actual run length.

The function also returns the run length in RCX (number of 1 bits in the contiguous run).

If you want the full run across arbitrary lengths, the C harness shows how to continue scanning and concatenating results to produce the full tree.

Limitations & safety

This is a purely bit-manipulation routine — no classified or sensitive behavior.

It works on arbitrary binary buffers; it does not attempt to unmask or reverse any cryptographic operation.

The contiguous-run result is limited in the primary return mask to 64 bits (convenient for bit ops). The harness shows how to extend across words.

