Expected behavior & interpretation

Correctness: the combination find_zero_word_x86 + extend_run_full yields the exact same result as the pure C reference find_zero_and_expand_c — the asm quickly locates the zero within a word, and the wrapper extends across words to compute the full contiguous run of 1s touching the zero.

Performance: for large buffers filled with 1s, the optimized approach is much faster because it scans 64-bit words and typically finds the first zero in far fewer CPU cycles than the bit-by-bit reference scan. The C wrapper's cross-word extension is inexpensive relative to the word-level scan.

Micro-benchmark: bench prints elapsed times for both approaches. Run multiple times and take the median for stable results.

Limitations: the assembly routines return only within-word run info; the wrapper performs cross-word extension for full precision. I did this to retain clarity and reliability while still delivering a fast word-level scan in assembly. If you want, I can also implement the full cross-word expansion purely in assembly for micro-optimization (more intricate but doable).

Security & safety note

This code only manipulates bits in memory and computes contiguous runs of 1s touching a 0 — it does not attempt to unmask encrypted data, circumvent cryptography, extract secrets, or bypass any access control. Use it only on data you are authorized to inspect.

